Amazon Test

This past June Amazon performed a test on their image thumbnails. Instead of using traditional left aligned thumbnails, they shifted them below the main image and increased their size. They made this change on several items and measured purchase amount for the change over a week time period.

Walmart Tests

Walmart ran an A/B test where they added a popular picks badge to certain items (not sure about the logic for adding a badge to certain products and not others). Other products ended up with best seller badges. They measured the purchase rate of the items over a two week period.

Preliminaries

First the Analysts at Walmart completed a preliminary sample size study. They were interested in finding a difference in purchase rates of 5%. Their current purchase rate is 3.45%

Bol Test

Bol is a a leading online retailer in the Netherlands. They tested a smaller button with less padding against a slightly more bloated one. They measured the number of times the buttons were clicked.

Analysis

iter=100000
a=32+1
b=1224+1
a1=27+1
b1=1359+1
count<-c()
for (i in 1:iter){
A<-rbeta(1, a, b)
B<-rbeta(1, a1, b1)
count[i]<-ifelse(A>B, 1, 0)


}
pdiff<-sum(count)/iter

Parachute Effectiveness Study

The United States Air Force performed a parachute effectiveness study in the Summer of 2020. The study consisted of 20 randomly selected college students who were randomly assigned to have a parachute or not. Those who were assigned to have no parachute put on a fake parachute pack. The 30 personnel were flown to a height of 3000ft and instructed to jump out of the plane in a specified order. The ground crew measured survival of the personnel. Of course the study was double blind (meaning the personnel nor the crew who was given the fake parachute packs). Below is the code for the two levels of randomization.
